[Merritt Clifton has provided the following comment in relation to the press report above and the fact that it has been established that the deceased organ donor died as a result of infection by a raccoon-variant rabies virus. - Mod.CP

"Raccoons are the species most commonly trapped for fur in the Carolinas and Florida, and that is also a raccoon rabies-endemic area. Raccoon trappers in the US usually use leghold traps. Usually they find the raccoon alive in the trap. They may kill the raccoon by drowning if near water and confident there are no alligators nearby (drowning is effected by dragging the trap into the water with a pole and then dragging it back out after the raccoon is dead), or by clubbing or shooting. (Drowning preserves the pelt; clubbing or shooting may damage the fur.). If the raccoon is clubbed or shot, the trapper will likely have contact with blood and brain tissue during skinning.

If the raccoon was collected as a roadkill, as indicated by [AM's] remark that, "He didn't care what the animal looked like. He picked it up," the likelihood of having contact with blood and brain tissue would be enhanced.

Trappers sometimes cut up the remains of the animals they catch for use as bait to catch others. Raccoons are not commonly eaten, but some people stew them. Cooking would of course kill the rabies virus, but preparation for cooking would not. Skinning and cutting up remains are both activities in which a trapper may cut himself on the hands. In cold climates trappers usually wear gloves, but in Florida and the Carolinas, most don't."]

