[2] Comment
Date: Tue 19 Mar 2013
From: Walter M Woolf <petsfly@aol.com> [edited]


[Re: ProMED-mail Rabies - USA: (MD) organ transplant 20130316.1589941]
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The recent identification of rabies virus in the brain tissue of an organ donor reminds me of the organ donor in Arkansas several years ago who was the source of the rabies virus that killed a number of organ recipients who had been immune suppressed prior to the receipt of the donated organs.

Recent evidence has also revealed that deceased animals of many species whose meat is used in less than developed countries will also contribute the rabies virus into humans, as even cooking the meat may not kill the virus in the meat products consumed by people. [I am unaware of instances of transmission via cooked food. - Mod.LM]

One wonders why "roadkill" and other deceased animal parts ever enter the food consumption chain ...what surprises me more is that a human who dies of an infectious process is ever considered as a suitable non-suspect organ donor.

The simple question emerges ... where was the "guard at the gate" in this recent episode of human tissue contributing rabies virus to unsuspecting recipients?

--
Walter M Woolf, VMD
Veterinarian
Tampa, Florida
USA
<petsfly@aol.com>

[ProMED-mail thanks Walter Woolf for his comment. - Mod.CP]

[3]
Date: 19 Mar 2013
From: T Jacob John <tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in> [Edited]

[Reply to Per Lausund, ProMED-mail Archive Number: 20130318.1592456]

You have raised a very pertinent question. Organ transplants demand is more than supply -- this is part of the problem. Short time for decisions is another.

But as you have pointed out, we need to expand the safety net. Blood and transplantation safety routinely checks donor for absence of HIV, HBV, HCV chronic infections. For any one with suspected infectious diseases of CNS one must include rabies virus, and whatever else might be relevant -- I can't offhand think of many. Acute encephalitis should alert about West Nile, and other locally prevalent viruses and they should also be included in the system.

I agree better protocol for recipient safety is needed under such circumstances.
--
T Jacob John,
Vellore, India>
